04568nam a22006975i 9780691187679DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911876797 a10.1515/97806911876792doi  a(DE-B1597)501916  a(OCoLC)1076460479  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSCI0340002bisacsh04a305.09442231 aCarson, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Measure of Merit :bTalents, Intelligence, and Inequality in the French and American Republics, 1750-1940 /cJohn Carson. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: MENTAL ABILITIES AND REPUBLICAN CULTURES -- tOne: "The most precious gift of nature" -- tTwo: Mental Capacities and Orthodox Minds -- tThree: All Men Are Created Equal? -- tPart II: INDIVIDUALIZING INTELLIGENCE THROUGH THE SCIENCE OF DIFFERENCE -- tFour: Between the Art of the Clinic and the Precision of the Laboratory -- tFive: American Psychology and the Seductions of IQ -- tPart III: MERIT, MATTER, AND MIND -- tSix: Out of the Lab and Into the World -- tSeven: Intelligence and the Politics of Merit between the Wars -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow have modern democracies squared their commitment to equality with their fear that disparities in talent and intelligence might be natural, persistent, and consequential? In this wide-ranging account of American and French understandings of merit, talent, and intelligence over the past two centuries, John Carson tells the fascinating story of how two nations wrestled scientifically with human inequalities and their social and political implications. Surveying a broad array of political tracts, philosophical treatises, scientific works, and journalistic writings, Carson chronicles the gradual embrace of the IQ version of intelligence in the United States, while in France, the birthplace of the modern intelligence test, expert judgment was consistently prized above such quantitative measures. He also reveals the crucial role that determinations of, and contests over, merit have played in both societies--they have helped to organize educational systems, justify racial hierarchies, classify army recruits, and direct individuals onto particular educational and career paths. A contribution to both the history of science and intellectual history, The Measure of Merit illuminates the shadow languages of inequality that have haunted the American and French republics since their inceptions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIntellectxSocial aspectszFrance. 0aIntellectxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aIntelligence levelsxSocial aspectszFrance. 0aIntelligence levelsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187679zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691187679423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187679.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK